= La quinta columna

Your own intelligence brings it, which is the only mercy in it: someone in one of your base villages — a place that fed the column, hid its wounded, buried its dead — is carrying information to the Colonel's paymaster. The evidence is good. It is also, being about a neighbor, the kind of evidence that has torn apart every guerrilla that ever had to weigh it.

This is the war the manuals do not cover: not the army, but the fracture the army buys inside the people you exist to defend. Handle it wrong in either direction — too soft and the village is an open book; too hard and you become the thing the villagers feared — and the zone is lost either way.

- @quinta_voltear: Turn them. A known informer fed false information is worth more than a dead one — run them back at the Colonel.
- @quinta_asamblea: The village's own justice. Lay the evidence before the assembly and let the people who were betrayed decide.
- @quinta_ajusticiar: The hard way, the fast way — and the way that has ended more guerrillas than the army ever did.

@quinta_voltear
go-to: post_event
choose-if: inteligencia >= 35
unavailable-subtitle: Running a double agent takes intelligence craft you have not built — 35.
on-arrival: coronel_red -= 10; inteligencia += 5; coronel_expuesto = 1; expediente += 2

You do not confront them; you feed them. For months the informer carries carefully cooked intelligence to the paymaster, and the Colonel's map of your zones acquires a precise, expensive wrongness — sweeps that hit empty ground, ambushes waiting where you never were. It is the hardest discipline in the war, to know a traitor and smile, and it is worth more than any execution: the enemy's eyes, turned to show him mirrors.

@quinta_asamblea
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: coronel_red -= 5; moral_columnas += 6; sup_peasants += 2; unity += 2

The evidence goes to the assembly because the betrayal was the village's before it was yours, and the village, given the truth and the choice, does what communities do better than tribunals: it does not kill, it *un-includes* — the informer and their family isolated, watched, cut from the web of trust that made the information worth selling, until they leave of their own weight. The Colonel loses a source and the village keeps its soul, which is the only victory in this that lasts.

@quinta_ajusticiar
go-to: post_event
on-arrival: coronel_red -= 6; moral_columnas -= 8; sup_peasants -= 4; memorial += 1; guerrilla_meter -= 2; unity -= 3

It is quick and it is certain and it is the beginning of the end, though that takes years to see. The source is closed. And the village learns that the column, too, can make a person disappear for a suspicion — that the difference between you and the state has narrowed to which side you are on, which is not a difference a frightened people will die for. Every guerrilla that chose this road walked the same slope afterward, downward, wondering when exactly it had become what it fought.

